Part I: Regression Assumptions

What regression assumptions can you test with each of the following displays?

  1. Histogram or Q-Q plot of residuals.

Answer:

Histogram and Q-Q plots of residuals are useful tools for assessing the normality, homoscedasticity, and linearity assumptions of linear regression.

1.Normality assumption: If the residuals are normally distributed, the histogram will resemble a bell-shaped curve and the Q-Q plot will be a straight line. Otherwise, the histogram will have an unusual shape, and the Q-Q plot will be curved.

2.Homoscedasticity assumption: If the residuals are homoscedastic, the histogram will show a roughly equal distribution of residuals above and below zero, and the Q-Q plot will have a roughly straight line. If the residuals are heteroscedastic, the histogram will show a skewed distribution of residuals, and the Q-Q plot will have a curved line.

3.Linearity assumption: If the relationship between the dependent variable and each independent variable is linear, the histogram and Q-Q plot of residuals will not show any discernible pattern.



  1. Plot of residuals against predicted values.

Answer:

The plot of residuals against predicted values (residuals vs. fitted) can be used to test the assumptions of linearity, homoscedasticity, and independence of a linear regression model.

1.Linearity: If the plot shows a random scatter of residuals around zero, it suggests that the linear assumption is valid. However, if there is a pattern or curvature in the plot, it indicates that the relationship between the variables is not linear.

2.Homoscedasticity: A random scatter of residuals around zero suggests that the homoscedasticity assumption is valid. However, if the residuals are not randomly scattered and show a cone shape, it indicates that the variability of the residuals is not constant, and there may be a violation of the homoscedasticity assumption.

3.Independence: If there is no pattern or correlation between the residuals in the plot, it suggests that the independence assumption is valid. However, if the plot shows a pattern or correlation between the residuals, it indicates that the residuals are not independent.



  1. Plot of residuals against each predictor.

Answer:

The plot of residuals against each predictor can be used to evaluate the linearity, independence, and homoscedasticity of the residuals, as well as to detect outliers and influential observations.

1.Linearity: If the points on the plot form a roughly straight line, this suggests that the relationship is linear.

2.Independence: If there is a clear pattern or trend in the residuals as the predictor variable changes, this suggests that the residuals are not independent and may violate the assumption of independence.

3.Homoscedasticity: If the residuals are homoscedastic, the points on the plot should be evenly scattered around a horizontal line, with no clear pattern of increasing or decreasing variability as the predictor variable changes.

4.Outliers and influential observations: Outliers are observations that are far away from the other observations and can have a large impact on the regression results. Influential observations are observations that have a large influence on the regression results, even if they are not outliers. These observations can be identified as points that are far away from the other points on the plot.



  1. Partial regression (or CERES) plots.

Answer:

Partial regression (or CERES) plots are a type of diagnostic plot that can be used to assess the assumptions of linear regression models. Specifically, they can be used to evaluate whether the relationship between the response variable and a particular predictor variable is linear, whether the residuals are normally distributed, and whether there is homoscedasticity of the residuals.

1.Linearity: The partial regression plot can be used to assess whether the relationship between the response variable and the predictor variable is linear. If the points on the plot form a straight line, this suggests that the relationship is linear.

2.Normality: The partial regression plot can also be used to assess whether the residuals are normally distributed. If the residuals are normally distributed, the points on the plot should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line at zero.

3.Homoscedasticity: The partial regression plot can be used to check for homoscedasticity of the residuals. If the residuals are homoscedastic, the points on the plot should be evenly scattered around the horizontal line at zero, with no clear pattern of increasing or decreasing variability as the predictor variable changes.

## F-statistic: 102.3 on 4 and 437 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

F-statistic: This is the value of the F-test statistic, which measures the ratio of the explained variance to the unexplained variance in the model. It indicates how well the model fits the data, with larger values indicating a better fit. In this case, the F-statistic is 102.3, which suggests a good fit of the model to the data.

DF: These values represent the degrees of freedom associated with the F-statistic. The first value (4) is the degrees of freedom associated with the numerator, which is the number of predictor variables in the model. The second value (437) is the degrees of freedom associated with the denominator, which is the residual degrees of freedom.

p-value: This is the probability of obtaining an F-statistic as large as the observed one, assuming that the null hypothesis (i.e., that all the coefficients in the model are zero) is true. A small p-value indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis, suggesting that at least one of the coefficients in the model is significantly different from zero. In this case, the p-value is very small (less than 2.2e-16), indicating strong evidence against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative hypothesis (i.e., that at least one of the coefficients in the model is different from zero).



  1. What is the interpretation of R2R2?

Answer:

R2R2 of this model is 0.48. This means that the four independent variables (primary caregiver’s education, partner’s education, hours of television watched per day, and income in dollars) in the model explain 48% of the variation in the dependent variable or Participant education.

7.2. Report on whether the results of each procedure indicated a violation of regression assumptions.

Independence Assumption:

From the independence assumption graphs and Durbin Watson test, it can be concluded that there is no significant autocorrelation in the residuals of the regression analysis.D-W statistic is 1.960802, which is very close to the expected value of 2 under the null hypothesis of no autocorrelation.


Linearity Assumption:

From the linearity assumption graphs, CERES plot and RESET test, it can be concluded that there is a violation of linearity assumption. We need to compute a non-linear version (via a power transformation) of the predictor variable(s) and add it to the model.


Normality Assumption:

From the Normality assumption graphs and Shapiro-Wilk normality test, it can be concluded that normality assumption is violated. Since the p-value in this case is very small (8.117e-07), it suggests strong evidence against the null hypothesis.

Homoscedasticity Assumption:

From the homoscedasticity assumption graphs and studentized Breusch-Pagan test, it can be concluded that homoscedasticity assumption is violated. The p-value of BP test is less than 0.05 which represents the probability of observing a BP statistic as extreme as 13.355, assuming the null hypothesis is true. This also suggests that there is heteroscedasticity present in the data.

The data set entitled Druguse.xlsx contains responses from 125 adolescents and their self-reported 1) illicit drug use behavior (druguse), 2) attitudes toward drug use and health (attitude), and 3) peer support (peersup). What follows are more formal definitions of the variables:

Name Description
druguse An index score of drug use severity designed for adolescent research (larger numbers indicate more severe drug use problems); outcome variable
attitude An ordinal variable ranging from 1 to 5. A score of 1 indicates that the adolescent believes that drugs are NOT harmful at all and a score of 5 indicates that the adolescent believes that drugs are extremely harmful; predictor variable
peersup An ordinal variable ranging from 1 to 5. A score of 1 indicates that the adolescent feels no peer support and a score of 5 indicates that the adolescent feels a great deal of peer support; predictor variable

From the above analysis, we can conclude that the interaction significantly contributes to the model fit. And both centered and not-centered R2R2 difference is the same.

library(ggplot2)


ggplot(druguse, aes(x = attitude_c, y = druguse, color = factor(peersup_c))) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Interaction Plot for Drug Use",
       x = "attitude_c",
       y = "druguse") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
